Here is the patch that fixes the bug in `UnmodifiableTrie.java`:

```diff
diff --git a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/collections4/trie/UnmodifiableTrie.java b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/collections4/trie/UnmodifiableTrie.java
index 3d78550c..38da62a7 100644
--- a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/collections4/trie/UnmodifiableTrie.java
+++ b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/collections4/trie/UnmodifiableTrie.java
@@ -52,6 +52,11 @@ public class UnmodifiableTrie<K, V> implements Trie<K, V>, Serializable, Unmodif
      * @throws IllegalArgumentException if trie is null
      */
     public static <K, V> UnmodifiableTrie<K, V> unmodifiableTrie(final Trie<K, ? extends V> trie) {
+        if (trie instanceof Unmodifiable) {
+            @SuppressWarnings("unchecked") // safe to upcast
+            final UnmodifiableTrie<K, V> tmpTrie = (UnmodifiableTrie<K, V>) trie;
+            return tmpTrie;
+        }
         return new UnmodifiableTrie<K, V>(trie);
     }
```

The fix adds a check in the `unmodifiableTrie` factory method to determine if the input trie is already an unmodifiable trie (by checking if it's an instance of the `Unmodifiable` interface). If it is, it returns the same instance directly instead of wrapping it again. This follows the same pattern used in other unmodifiable collection implementations in the codebase, such as `UnmodifiableMap`.

This resolves the issue where `assertSame("UnmodifiableTrie shall not be decorated", trie, TrieUtils.unmodifiableTrie(trie))` was failing in the test, since the method was creating a new wrapper instead of returning the existing unmodifiable trie instance.

